As shown in Fig. 7a, the development trend of the six penetration curves was consistent at a certain temperature $(298 \mathrm{~K})$ and concentration $\left(85.21 \mathrm{~m}^{3} \mathrm{~g}^{-1}\right)$. Specifically, the curve started very gently, while the concentration increased dramatically as soon as the breakthrough occurred. With the passage of time, a gradual stabilization in concentration was observed. The adsorption capacity of $\mathrm{AC}-\mathrm{MgO}-10 \%$ ranks the first among all the samples. Breakthrough time is defined as time when outlet concentration was $10 \%$ of inlet concentration. ${ }^{45}$ The breakthrough time was also different for each sample, and the breakthrough time of acetone in $\mathrm{AC}-\mathrm{MgO}-10 \%$ is the longest, suggesting its superior acetone capture capacity.

Here, the Langmuir equation, which considers monolayer adsorption on a homogeneous surface with negligible intermolecular force, ${ }^{46}$ was used to fit the adsorption isotherms of acetone on the samples, and the Langmuir equation is expressed as follows:

\[
\frac{C_{\mathrm{e}}}{q_{\mathrm{e}}}=\frac{1}{q_{\mathrm{m}} K_{\mathrm{L}}}+\frac{C_{\mathrm{e}}}{q_{\mathrm{m}}}
\]

where $C_{\mathrm{e}}\left(\mathrm{g} \mathrm{m}^{-3}\right)$ refers to the equilibrium concentration, $q_{\mathrm{e}}$ $\left(\mathrm{mg} \mathrm{g}^{-1}\right)$ is the amount of adsorbate on per unit weight of adsorbent, $q_{\mathrm{m}}\left(\mathrm{mg} \mathrm{g}^{-1}\right)$ is the monolayer adsorption capacity, and $K_{\mathrm{L}}\left(\mathrm{m}^{3} \mathrm{~g}^{-1}\right)$ is a constant related to adsorption rate. The fitting results are listed in Table 2 .

As shown, the experimental data were consistent with Langmuir equation. By varying the acetone concentration (9.56$\left.85.21 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}\right)$ at a fixed temperature $(298 \mathrm{~K})$, a set of adsorption isotherms were obtained for all samples (shown in Fig. 7b). According to the linear regression method, the Langmuir equations are suitable for the adsorption of acetone $\left(R^{2}>0.993\right)$. Apparently, type-I profiles were observed in all adsorption isotherms of acetone in accordance with IUPAC classification,

