Fig. 9 Optimized structures of (I): (a) acetone, (b) MgO and (c) graphene, and (II): (d) acetone-graphene, (e) acetone-MgO, (f) acetone-MgO/ graphene. In addition, we compared the abilities of pure $\mathrm{MgO}$ and $\mathrm{AC}-$ $\mathrm{MgO}$ composite samples in acetone capture, which presented with diverse surface area and $\mathrm{MgO}$ content (at $298 \mathrm{~K}, 85.21 \mathrm{~m}^{3}$ $\mathrm{g}^{-1}$ acetone) (see Fig. 8). Consequently, it varied significantly in view of the capacities of acetone adsorption from six samples under certain situations.

There is no doubt that the presence of $\mathrm{MgO}$ species as well as the surface area is actively involved in the determination of capacity of acetone adsorption. Of note, there is a decline in surface area along with an elevation in $\mathrm{MgO}$ content. This is due to the gradual block of the pore in the activated carbon attributed from the increase in the number of $\mathrm{MgO}$ nanoparticles. As shown in Fig. 8, we compared the adsorption capacity of $\mathrm{AC}-$ $\mathrm{MgO}$ composites and unmodified activated carbon. As a result, the AC-0 sample presented with a capacity of acetone adsorption at $315 \mathrm{mg} \mathrm{g}^{-1}$, and the $\mathrm{AC}-\mathrm{MgO}-10 \%$ sample ranked first in capacity of acetone uptake at $433 \mathrm{mg} \mathrm{g}^{-1}$, which harbored intermediate surface area $\left(1067 \mathrm{~m}^{2} \mathrm{~g}^{-1}\right)$ as well as $\mathrm{MgO}$ content (10 $\mathrm{wt} \%)$. In consideration of the Lewis-base active sites provided by $\mathrm{MgO}$ nanoparticles, ${ }^{52,53}$ which play a vital role in binding the acidic acetone, the advantage of higher $\mathrm{MgO}$ content is more obvious even if the specific surface area of AC$\mathrm{MgO}-10 \%$ is smaller than that of AC-0. However, the pure $\mathrm{MgO}$ sample, with the highest $\mathrm{MgO}$ content $(100 \mathrm{wt} \%)$ but the smallest surface area $\left(120 \mathrm{~m}^{3} \mathrm{~g}^{-1}\right)$, displayed the lowest acetone uptake capacity at $201 \mathrm{mg} \mathrm{g}^{-1}$. The reason is that the surface area of pure $\mathrm{MgO}$ is too small to expose enough active sites of $\mathrm{MgO}$ surface. The above finding indicates that the surface area is also involved in acetone adsorption. Collectively, the acetone adsorption capacity of AC modified by $\mathrm{MgO}$ depends on the $\mathrm{MgO}$ content as well as the surface area.

\subsection{Molecular modeling study}
In order to prove that the acetone adsorption on $\mathrm{MgO}$-doped activated carbon samples is not only the physical adsorption but also chemical adsorption tendency, the adsorption of acetone molecules on the surface of activated carbon, $\mathrm{MgO}$ and MgO-graphene composites was simulated using DFT method. After fully optimization by the GGA-PBE method and considering all the spatial positional relationships between adsorbate and adsorbent, optimized structures were obtained (see Fig. 9). The result of molecular interaction of acetone with graphene surface is shown in Fig. S1. $\dagger$ Obviously, interaction between acetone and graphene is very weak even in different adsorption modes. However, from Fig. S2, $\dagger$ molecular interaction of acetone with $\mathrm{MgO}$ surface, we can see that $\mathrm{O}$ and $\mathrm{H}$ atoms in acetone interact more easily with $\mathrm{Mg}$ and $\mathrm{O}$ atoms on the edge sites at $\mathrm{MgO}$ surface, respectively, which is the best adsorption mode. The surface reactivity of the MgO strongly depends to the site selected for the molecule adsorption. The $\mathrm{MgO}$ face without defects has a low reactivity producing a weak adsorption but the adsorption on steps, edges and corners is stronger. ${ }^{54}$ The same applies to acetone-MgO/graphene system (see Fig. S3†).

After geometry optimization of the functionalized carbon surface, acetone adsorption energy on the surface was calculated. The values of adsorption energy for acetone complexes with surface models are given in Table 4. The greater the negative value of adsorption energy, the stronger the adsorption capacity is. ${ }^{55}$ As shown, acetone molecule exhibits the stronger interaction with pure $\mathrm{MgO}$ with the energy value of $-107.89 \mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$, which is categorized in the region of chemisorption, while the values of adsorption is given $-4.20 \mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$ for pristine graphene, which is categorized at physisorption region. ${ }^{56}$ This can be attributed to the pure MgO nanoparticles providing the active adsorption sites of Lewis base for acidic gas acetone. ${ }^{57}$ Notably, the highest binding energy occurs in the acetone- $\mathrm{MgO}$ /graphene system, $-118.13 \mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$, and the energy value is larger than the sum of the other two systems. As suggested by the results, the interaction between $\mathrm{MgO}$ and graphene can promote the adsorption of acetone.

The local charge distribution of acetone molecule before and after adsorption has been calculated with the GGA-PBE method so as to confirm the Lewis acid-base interaction between acetone and MgO nanoparticles (Fig. 10). Through comparing the charge distribution of separate acetone molecule with its complexes, it can be found that the electronic structure of acetone molecule is subjected to charges upon adsorption. As is shown in Fig. 10, acetone molecule carries the highest negative charges in the electronic structure after interacting with $\mathrm{MgO}$ graphene model. The net charges are transferred from the surface of $\mathrm{MgO}$-graphene (the electron pair donor) to acetone

